JOHANNESBURG - Eight officials from South African Social Security Agency (Sassa) have been arrested in Mpumalanga for fraud.They allegedly manipulated the system to pay out grants of more than R5.5-million to people who did not qualify.Hawks spokesman Dineo Lucy Sekgotodi said the suspects allegedly manipulated the system by registering able-bodied people as people living with disabilities. The suspects defrauded the state with more than R5.5-million. The investigations into the matter was started in December 2015, said Sekgotodi.The suspects will appear in the Tonga magistrate's court on Friday.African News Agency